summary: Meet Jodie Comer, the Doctor Foster mistress starring in this year's most fashionable TV show
title: Meet Jodie Comer, the Doctor Foster mistress starring in this year's most fashionable TV show
excerpt: Jodie Comer is one minute and six seconds into her Stella interview, conducted over a loaded Caesar salad in a west London café, when a fan approaches.
description: “It’s so competitive for parts like this, no one wants to play just the wife, or the girlfriend,’ she considers of the fact that actresses are now fighting and working hard to get meatier parts. ‘We all want the roles that are challenging and don’t show women as one-dimensional. I’ve been so lucky that three of the most recent roles I’ve played have all been written by women. Female writers understand the female psyche and can write those characters better. I don’t know any actor who wouldn’t want the opportunity to play this character.”

summary: But mainly I rage at myself for my own ability to let things slide because I’d rather be ‘nice’ than stand up for myself in an...
text: But mainly I rage at myself for my own ability to let things slide because I’d rather be ‘nice’ than stand up for myself in an uncomfortable situation. My characters have streaks of fearlessness. I get a rush writing women who don’t care what you think. Probably to help me grow into being one.
source: Phoebe Waller-Bridge, on what makes her rage

summary: okay...ya know what....ya know what I'm just gonna say it...killing eve was very good except for the fact that...I don't think...
body: okay…ya know what….ya know what I’m just gonna say it…killing eve was very good except for the fact that…I don’t think the show spent enough time building on the connection between eve/villanelle…like…this is supposed to be a sort of silence of the lambs type deal but Hannibal Lecter became obsessed with Clarice Starling over time, they spent a lot of time together, relatively, certainly more time than he’d spent with anyone else, other than the orderly, so the obsession made sense. However, I didn’t feel/see that same buildup in the relationship between Eve & Villanelle so I can’t really get into it ??? & it is irritating af & honestly I feel more for Eve’s mentors, Bill & Carolyn than I do for Eve

body:
The thing about Niko is, he wants Eve to be safe.

The thing about Oksana is, she wants to not kill Eve.

The thing about Eve is, she cares significantly more about one of those things than the other.

X

Or: Eve Polastri conducts a totally objective self-analysis, and Oksana Astankova has her questioning everything. Literally. Sort of.
